        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(ollama): release stream reader lock to prevent resource leak",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts` acquires a `ReadableStreamDefaultReader` via `response.body.getReader()` inside a try block, but the finally block that calls `release()` did not call `reader.releaseLock()`. Per the Streams specification, `reader.cancel()` rejects pending reads but does NOT release the lock — `releaseLock()` is required to allow other consumers to acquire the stream.\n\nAdditionally, the original `const reader` declaration inside the try block caused a TypeScript error: the finally block cannot reference a const that is not guaranteed to be assigned in all code paths.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts`: hoist reader before try → `let reader: ReadableStreamDefaultReader<Uint8Array> | undefined`; assign inside try; use `reader?.releaseLock()` in finally\n- `test/_proof_ollama_stream_lock.mts`: Web Streams lock lifecycle proof (5 PASS, 0 FAIL)\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Real behavior proof — Web Streams lock lifecycle (L2)\n\nProves the exact Streams specification behavior that this fix addresses:\n\n```\n$ node --import tsx test/_proof_ollama_stream_lock.mts\n\nPASS  fresh stream: not locked\nPASS  after getReader: stream is locked\nPASS  after reader.cancel(): stream still locked :: locked=true\nPASS  after reader.releaseLock(): stream unlocked :: locked=false\nPASS  new reader: can acquire after lock released :: locked=true\n\n[proof] 5 PASS, 0 FAIL\n```\n\nThis demonstrates that `reader.cancel()` alone does NOT release the lock — `reader.releaseLock()` is mandatory per the WHATWG Streams specification. Without it, the underlying stream remains locked after the function returns, preventing reuse or garbage collection.",
